excerpt: Colossal parliament building & international conference center known for its ornate interior.
detail_description: The Palace of Parliament is a colossal building and international conference center with an ornate interior. It was constructed in a traumatic transformation for the city, leading to the destruction of churches, homes, and displacement of families. This mega construction dreamt up by late dictator Nicolae Ceausescu is considered the heaviest building in the world, using massive amounts of steel, marble, and sand sourced locally.
name: Palace of Parliament

excerpt: Ethnographic museum devoted to Romanian village life, with hundreds of peasant farms & homes.
detail_description: The Dimitrie Gusti National Village Museum, also known as the 'Village Museum,' is an open-air museum located in Herastrau Park that showcases traditional Romanian village life. Established in 1936, the museum features over 300 traditional buildings such as peasant homes, barns, log cabins, churches, workshops, and mills from various regions of Romania. These structures were carefully dismantled and reassembled within the park to create a lifelike village setting.
name: "Dimitrie Gusti" National Village Museum
address: Şoseaua Pavel D. Kiseleff 30, București 011347, Romania

excerpt: Iconic neoclassical concert hall opened in 1888 hosting the George Enescu Philharmonic Orchestra.
detail_description: The Romanian Athenaeum is a neoclassical concert hall that has been a symbol of national culture for over 120 years. Designed by French architect Albert Galleron, it was funded through a public subscription and national lottery. Located in Revolution Square, it is surrounded by important landmarks such as the former Royal Palace (now the National Museum of Art) and the Memorial of Rebirth.
name: The Romanian Athenaeum

excerpt: Orthodox monastery & church from 1724, partly rebuilt in the early 1900s after earthquake damage.
detail_description: The Church of the "Stavropoleos" Monastery, located in Bucharest's old center, is a nunnery with a rich history dating back to 1724. The monastery features stunning hand-painted frescoes and embodies the Romanian Brancovenesc architectural style, blending late Renaissance, Byzantine, Ottoman, and Baroque influences. Visitors can soak in the serene atmosphere and relax in the charming courtyard.
name: The Church of the "Stavropoleos" Monastery

excerpt: Bucharest’s grand Old Town is home to Vlad the Impaler’s former court at Curtea Veche, now an open-air museum of excavated medieval ruins, and the National Museum of Romanian History showing religious icons and royal treasures in a former palace. Shops sell local wines and beaded jewelry, while elegant restaurants in 19th-century buildings serve traditional dishes. Buzzing pubs and discos draw crowds after dark.
detail_description: Old Town, also known as the Historical Center of Bucharest, is a beloved and attractive area in the city steeped in neoclassical and neo-baroque style buildings. It features terraces, cafes, restaurants, shops, and historical landmarks such as Vlad the Impaler’s former court at Curtea Veche. The area offers a mix of open-air museums showcasing medieval ruins and former palaces turned into museums displaying religious icons and royal treasures.
name: Old Town

detail_description: Bucharest Herăstrău Park, home to the oldest man-made lake in the city, offers a 7.4-kilometer scenic path along its banks. The park features magnificent cypress trees, numerous cafes and restaurants, playgrounds for children, and sports grounds including old-school workout equipment. Visitors can enjoy a leisurely walk around the lake or engage in activities like cycling, kayaking, and canoeing.
name: Bucharest Herăstrău Park
address: Şoseaua Pavel D. Kiseleff 32, București 014192, Romania

excerpt: Historical artifacts including a cast of Trajan's Column, Romania's national treasury & Greek gold.
detail_description: The National Museum of Romanian History is a must-visit in Bucharest, offering an extensive collection of historical artifacts that provide insight into the country's rich heritage. Spanning 8,000 square meters and approximately 60 exhibition rooms, the museum showcases archaeological evidence dating back to the Paleolithic era and delves into the material and spiritual culture of the Geto-Dacians.
name: National Museum of Romanian History

excerpt: Paintings & sculpture from medieval & modern Romania, Western Europe, the Islamic world & East Asia.
detail_description: The Romanian National Museum of Art is home to a world-class collection of Romanian art, from medieval to modern times. The museum's European galleries contain works by some of the greatest names in art history, such as Lucas Cranach the Elder and Jan van Eyck. The museum also houses a rich collection of Romanian medieval art and modern Romanian art.
name: National Museum of Art

excerpt: Natural history museum with Black Sea & Atlantic wildlife dioramas, plus a humpback whale skeleton.
detail_description: The "Grigore Antipa" National Museum of Natural History, situated near Piata Victoriei in Bucharest, is a renowned institution dedicated to biodiversity research and public education. Established in 1834 at the behest of Great Ban Mihalache Ghica, it houses an impressive collection of well-crafted exhibits including wildlife dioramas featuring Black Sea and Atlantic species, as well as a humpback whale skeleton.
name: Grigore Antipa National Museum of Natural History
address: Şoseaua Pavel D. Kiseleff 1, București 011341, Romania

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Bucharest's Old Town, Cărturești Carusel is a breathtaking bookstore that has been meticulously renovated to create a stunning literary haven. The six-story building boasts a bright and airy interior, with balconies overlooking a soaring atrium. Visitors can explore tens of thousands of titles and find cozy nooks to immerse themselves in books. Additionally, the top floor houses a bistro for those seeking sustenance for both body and mind.
name: Cărturești Carusel

excerpt: Collections of folk costumes, ceramics & icons explore Romanian culture in a stately 1941 building.
detail_description: The National Museum of the Romanian Peasant, housed in a grand 1941 building, showcases an extensive collection of folk costumes, ceramics, and icons that offer insight into Romanian culture. This museum is one of the notable representatives of traditional architecture in Bucharest. It stands alongside other architectural landmarks such as the Lahovari House, Central School, and Doina House. The museum provides a fascinating exploration of Romanian heritage within its stately walls.
name: The National Museum of the Romanian Peasant
address: Şoseaua Pavel D. Kiseleff 3, București, Romania

detail_description: Calea Victoriei, also known as the Victory Way, is a prestigious boulevard in central Bucharest, Romania. It holds historical significance and was once a bustling street lined with elegant baroque houses and high-end shops. The avenue stretches from Revolution Square to the Dambovita River, featuring posh shopping outlets, cafes, restaurants, cultural venues, and art galleries. In its northern section are stately residences while the southern end hosts most of the entertainment establishments.
name: Calea Victoriei

excerpt: This tree-filled, English-style park with a lake, rose garden & pavilion is a tranquil destination.
detail_description: Cismigiu Gardens is a serene and picturesque English-style park in Bucharest, offering a peaceful retreat with its tree-filled landscapes, a charming lake, and a delightful rose garden. It's one of the city's must-visit attractions alongside iconic landmarks like the Palace of Parliament and the Dimitrie Gusti National Village Museum. The park provides an ideal setting for leisurely strolls along its winding paths, scenic ponds, and numerous seating areas.
name: Cismigiu Gardens

excerpt: Architecturally notable Romanian restaurant with wood paneling, stained-glass windows & a patio.
detail_description: Caru' cu Bere is a renowned Romanian restaurant known for its impressive architecture, featuring wood paneling, stained-glass windows, and a charming patio. It is considered one of Bucharest's oldest restaurants and boasts a stunning interior adorned with frescoes, stained glass, and vaulted ceilings. The establishment has historical significance as it was opened in the late 19th century by Nicolae Mircea after being inspired by Bavarian beer houses during his apprenticeship in Bucharest.
name: Caru' cu bere

excerpt: Bucharest, in southern Romania, is the country's capital and commercial center. Its iconic landmark is the massive, communist-era Palatul Parlamentului government building, which has 1,100 rooms. Nearby, the historic Lipscani district is home to an energetic nightlife scene as well as tiny Eastern Orthodox Stavropoleos Church and 15th-century Curtea Veche Palace, where Prince Vlad III (“The Impaler”) once ruled.
detail_description: Bucharest, the capital and commercial hub of Romania, boasts the imposing Palatul Parlamentului government building from the communist era. The Lipscani district offers a vibrant nightlife scene and is home to the Stavropoleos Church and Curtea Veche Palace. Rue du Pain Boulangerie Artisanale, Bucharest's first French bakery, serves artisanal products with premium ingredients in a cozy bistro setting.
name: Bucharest

excerpt: 27-m high granite arch built in memory of WWI troops, with internal stairs for city views.
detail_description: The Triumphal Arch, a 27-meter high granite structure located in Bucharest, Romania, serves as a powerful symbol of the country's independence and resilience. Built in 1936 to commemorate the reunification of Romania in 1918, this iconic monument echoes the grandeur of its Parisian counterpart. Adorned with intricate carvings and sculptures that honor significant events in Romanian history, the arch stands as a testament to national pride and solidarity.
name: Arcul de Triumf
address: Piața Arcul de Triumf, București 011453, Romania

detail_description: Strada Lipscani, located in the Old Town, is a bustling pedestrian area filled with an array of attractions. Visitors can explore rooftop restaurants, quaint coffee shops, and delightful bakeries while soaking up the charming atmosphere. The street also boasts lively music venues and friendly locals, making it a popular spot for enjoying the vibrant nightlife at its bars, pubs, and clubs.
name: Strada Lipscani

excerpt: This functioning religious & civic landmark hosts a popular Palm Sunday pilgrimage & other services.
detail_description: The Patriarchal Cathedral is a significant religious and civic landmark that holds a popular Palm Sunday pilgrimage and various other services. It is part of a building complex that includes the Patriarchal Palace, offering visitors an impressive sight. The area also features attractions like the Carturesti bookstore, University Square, Sfantul Anton church, Lipscani neighborhood for nightlife, Herastrau Park, Cismigiu Park, and Bellu Cemetery.
name: Patriarchal Cathedral of Bucharest

excerpt: Early 19th-century palace exhibiting varied private art collections donated to the Romanian state.
detail_description: The Museum of Art Collections is located in a 19th-century palace and showcases a diverse range of private art collections donated to the Romanian state. The museum features an extensive art collection with works by renowned Romanian masters such as Nicolae Grigorescu, Theodor Aman, and Nicolae Tonitza. It also houses art objects from Asia and the Middle East, including a notable Van Gogh drawing.
name: Museum of Art Collections

excerpt: A regular site for protests & events, this spacious plaza is surrounded by historic buildings.
detail_description: University's Square is a spacious plaza in Bucharest, surrounded by historic buildings and serving as a regular site for protests and events. It is divided by Ion C. Bratianu Boulevard, linking it to Unirii Square. The area around the square is part of the old princely court nucleus, with bustling and quieter halves ready to receive attention from visitors. Visitors can explore the narrow streets of the historic center to discover its old stories and eclectic charm.
name: University's Square

excerpt: A cover of yellow glass tops this dramatic 19th-century passageway lined with pubs & restaurants.
detail_description: Macca - Vilacrosse Passage, formerly known as the Jewelry Passage, is a charming covered passageway in Bucharest. It connects Calea Victoriei to Strada Lipscani and is lined with various restaurants, cafes, and bars. The 19th-century passage features an elegant stained-glass ceiling and a beautiful rotunda with graceful archways. At night, the space is illuminated by warm overhead orbs, creating a romantic atmosphere.
name: Macca - Vilacrosse Passage

excerpt: Landmark 1800s cemetery with ornate funerary sculptures & the tombs of many illustrious Romanians.
detail_description: Bellu Cemetery, an 1800s landmark in Bucharest, is often compared to Paris' Pere Lachaise Cemetery. It serves as the final resting place for numerous renowned Romanians, including writers and actors. Visitors flock to see the tombs of national poet Mihai Eminescu and singer Maria Tanase. The cemetery's ornate marble monuments depict tragic or romantic tales, such as the Poroineanu family's tombstone narrating a story of forbidden love.
name: Bellu Cemetery

excerpt: Palace-turned-museum featuring exhibits on the life of the famous Romanian musician George Enuscu.
detail_description: The George Enescu National Museum, housed in the Cantacuzino Palace, is a stunning Beaux-Arts/Art Nouveau building in Bucharest. Originally built for Prime Minister Gheorghe Grigore Cantacuzino, it boasts an exquisite facade and an oyster-shaped glass entrance designed by architect Ion D. Berindei. The museum showcases exhibits on the life of renowned Romanian musician George Enescu and offers visitors a glimpse into the city's aristocratic past.
name: George Enescu National Museum

detail_description: In Bucharest, Romania, the Arcul de Triumf stands proudly in the northern part of the city. It has a rich history, with its first wooden construction dating back to 1878 to celebrate Romania's independence. After being rebuilt in 1922 following World War I, it has become an important landmark. Visitors can enjoy a panoramic view of the city from its terrace.
name: Arcul de Triumf
address: Bulevardul Mareșal Constantin Prezan, București, Romania

detail_description: Bucharest Old Town is a charming and historically preserved area that offers a glimpse into the past of the Romanian capital. Despite being relatively small, it boasts a maze of narrow pedestrian lanes that exude an old-world charm. Unlike other parts of the city, Old Town was spared from destruction during World War 2 and modernization projects. Visitors can explore numerous churches and immerse themselves in the area's characteristic atmosphere.
name: Old Town

excerpt: Public green space with cafes, restaurants & gardens around a large lake used for water sports.
detail_description: King Mihai I Park, also known as Herastrau Park, is a sprawling green space covering approximately 190 hectares in north-central Bucharest. It surrounds the picturesque Lake Herastrau and offers a variety of attractions for both locals and tourists. The park features charming lakeside cafes and restaurants, making it a popular destination for leisurely strolls and outdoor dining.
name: "King Michael I" Park

excerpt: Scenic park established in 1906 featuring a French garden, historical monuments, a mausoleum & lake.
detail_description: "Carol I" Park, located in the southern-central area of Bucharest on Filaret Hill, is a historic park established in 1906. It offers a French garden, historical monuments, and a picturesque lake spread across 41 hectares. The park features generous walkways for walking, cycling, and rollerblading as well as playgrounds for children. Visitors can admire important monuments such as the Mausoleum housing fallen soldiers from World War II and the Roman Arenas.
name: Carol I Park

excerpt: Landscaped gardens featuring rare & exotic plants, with waterfalls, a herbarium & vast greenhouses.
detail_description: The Dimitrie Brândză Botanical Garden in Bucharest is a must-visit destination for nature enthusiasts. This stunning garden boasts an impressive collection of over 10,000 plant species, including rare and exotic varieties. Visitors can explore landscaped gardens, waterfalls, and vast greenhouses filled with a diverse array of plants. The garden also features aquatic plants, outdoor tropical flora, and species from hot regions.
name: "Dimitrie Brândză" Botanical Garden

excerpt: Former private collection of 19th- & 20th-century Romanian & French art, including Matisse & Renoir.
detail_description: The Zambaccian Art Museum, a former private collection turned into a branch of the National Art Museum, showcases an exceptional array of 19th- and 20th-century Romanian and French art. The relatively small museum boasts iconic works by renowned artists such as Matisse, Renoir, Picasso, and Cezanne alongside masterpieces by Romanian painters like Luchian, Pallady, Tonitza, and Petrascu.
name: Zambaccian Art Museum

excerpt: Red-brick Orthodox church with bell towers dating to the 1720s, plus later icons & interior frescos.
detail_description: Located in Revolution Square, Kretzulescu Church is a striking Orthodox church dating back to the 1720s. Its red-brick facade and bell towers stand as a testament to its enduring history. Built in the Brancovenesc style, it has survived bombings, demolitions during the communist era, revolutions, and earthquakes. Commissioned by the Cretulescu family, this small yet historically rich church boasts later icons and interior frescoes that have remained untouched by wars or disasters.
name: Kretzulescu Church

excerpt: Orthodox monastery in Brâncovenesc style dating to 1715 with carved wooden doors & a museum.
detail_description: Antim Monastery, a stunning Orthodox monastery in Brâncovenesc style, was established in 1715 and is known for its intricately carved wooden doors and a captivating museum. The monastery's founder, Antim Ivireanu, was a remarkable figure of the 18th century - a polyglot, talented craftsman, printer, and bishop who played a significant role in the Romanian Orthodox Church.
name: "Antim" Monastery
address: Strada Mitropolit Antim Ivireanul 29, București 040111, Romania

excerpt: Indoor & outdoor clusters of stalls selling produce, handicrafts, clothing & baked goods.
detail_description: Obor Market is a bustling marketplace located in Communist Bucharest, offering a wide variety of goods and services. As you stroll through the indoor and outdoor clusters of stalls, you'll find everything from produce and handicrafts to clothing and baked goods. This market is renowned as the largest peasant market in Bucharest, providing an array of items that showcase Romanian culture.
name: Obor Market

excerpt: Busy square & traffic hub with a small park & monumental fountains, bisected by a wide boulevard.
detail_description: Piața Unirii is a bustling square and transportation center featuring a small park and grand fountains, divided by a wide boulevard. It's situated in several interesting districts for tourists, including Districts 1, 3, 4, and 6. The square offers views of the imposing Palace of Parliament, an emblem of Romania's communist era with a controversial history involving the demolition of thousands of homes.
name: Piața Unirii

excerpt: Protected lakeland with walking paths, plus hides for spotting marsh harriers, moorhens & coots.
detail_description: Văcărești Nature Park, the first urban nature park in Romania, was established in 2016 through the efforts of the Văcărești Nature Park Association. Situated just five kilometers from downtown Bucharest, this protected lakeland spans 183 hectares and features walking paths and observation hides for birdwatching. The park's creation involved reclaiming land that had been abandoned after a Communist-era hydro-technic project.
name: "Văcărești" Natural Park

excerpt: Narrow passageway with open-air cafes & a canopy of suspended, rainbow-colored umbrellas.
detail_description: Pasajul Victoria is a charming narrow passageway in Bucharest, adorned with open-air cafes and a striking canopy of suspended, rainbow-colored umbrellas. This hidden gem gained popularity through social media posts, attracting numerous visitors and bloggers to its picturesque setting. It has become one of the most sought-after streets in Bucharest, offering a delightful atmosphere for locals and tourists alike to enjoy the vibrant surroundings and cozy cafes.
name: Pasajul Victoria

excerpt: Hip rooftop venue with a global menu featuring pasta, burgers & meat dishes, plus creative drinks.
detail_description: Linea | Closer To The Moon is a popular rooftop bar located at the top of Victoria department store in Bucharest, offering stunning panoramic views of the city. It features a global menu with pasta, burgers, and meat dishes, along with creative drinks. The venue hosts various events including live music gigs and showcases some of the best DJs.
name: Linea | Closer To The Moon

detail_description: Food Hood in Bucharest, Romania is a trendy spot that embraces the North American concept of food trucks combined with bars and live music. The venue hosts various events such as yoga sessions, badminton games, and record fairs. It offers a casual atmosphere with outdoor seating and occasional live music performances. Modelier serves affordable burgers and cocktails, while Food Hood features food trucks, beer, and communal dining areas popular among local hipsters.
name: Food Hood

detail_description: The Muzeul „Micul Paris” is a treasure trove of art from the Belle Epoque era. It's well worth your time to visit and it's great to have a culturally well-rounded guide like 60-year-old David as your tour guide.
name: The Little Paris Museum | Bucharest

detail_description: Strada Pictor Arthur Verona is a charming street in Bucharest, Romania, known for its vibrant atmosphere and cultural attractions. It's located near Stavropoleos Monastery and Kretzulescu Church, making it a great place to explore the city's religious heritage. The street is also close to popular spots like Carturesti bookstore and Obor Market, where visitors can immerse themselves in local culture.
name: Strada Pictor Arthur Verona

detail_description: Berăria H Herastrau is a vibrant restaurant and beer hall located in the heart of Bucharest's lush Herastrau Park. Families are drawn to its cheerful atmosphere and spacious, kid-friendly environment. The venue hosts a variety of events, including concerts catering to different tastes. Guests can enjoy a good selection of fresh beers and tasty food while taking in the lively ambiance.
name: Berăria H Herăstrău
address: "King Michael I" Park, Şoseaua Pavel D. Kiseleff 32, București 011343, Romania

excerpt: Opulent 80-room former residence of Romanian president Ceausescu, built in 1964, with lush gardens.
detail_description: The Ceaușescu House, located in Bucharest, Romania, is a captivating museum that offers a glimpse into the opulent lifestyle of Nicolae Ceaușescu, Romania's former communist leader, and his wife Elena. This historic residence was their private mansion and now showcases luxurious furnishings, extravagant decor, and personal artifacts from the Ceaușescu regime. Visitors can explore the 80-room villa and lush gardens with political and cultural significance.
name: "Ceaușescu" House

excerpt: Science-based exhibits & optical tricks in a family-friendly museum with magic mirrors & holograms.
detail_description: The Museum of Senses, situated in central Bucharest, offers an interactive and playful experience for visitors of all ages. With 13 rooms and over 40 exhibits, the museum invites guests to explore mind-bending optical illusions, sensory displays, and thought-provoking installations. From a Vortex tunnel to an infinity mirror room, visitors can test their perception in fun ways. The venue aims to awaken senses and inspire discovery through its whimsical approach to reality and perception.
name: Muzeul Simțurilor
address: Bulevardul General Paul Teodorescu 4, București 061346, Romania

excerpt: Restored 6-floor national theater complex, open since 1973, with 6 halls & an outdoor amphitheater.
detail_description: The Ion Luca Caragiale National Theatre, also known as TNB, is a prominent cultural landmark in Bucharest. The modern 6-floor complex boasts six halls and an outdoor amphitheater, offering a diverse range of performances from classic plays to contemporary productions. Originally inaugurated in 1852 and reconstructed between 2010 and 2014, it stands as the largest theatre edifice in Europe.
name: "Ion Luca Caragiale" National Theatre

excerpt: Early 1700s Orthodox church with frescoes, mosaics & the ornate tomb of Constantin Brâncoveanu.
detail_description: The New 'Saint George' Church is a stunning Orthodox church in Bucharest, dating back to the early 1700s. It features exquisite frescoes, mosaics, and the ornate tomb of Constantin Brâncoveanu. Situated on the ruins of an older church, it has been restored several times due to earthquake damage. The architecture is a beautiful example of its time and offers a serene atmosphere for visitors.
name: The New "Saint George" Church

excerpt: Collection of contemporary works by Romanian & other artists, plus eclectic temporary shows.
detail_description: MNAC – Muzeul Național de Artă Contemporană al României, located inside the Palace of Parliament, offers a diverse collection of contemporary works by Romanian and Eastern European artists. The museum showcases an eclectic mix of temporary exhibitions alongside its permanent collection. Visitors to Bucharest can explore MNAC as part of a cultural tour that includes other notable museums such as the National Museum of Art of Romania and the Dimitrie Gusti National Village Museum.
name: MNAC – Muzeul Național de Artă Contemporană al României
address: Palatul Parlamentului, Intrarea E1, Calea 13 Septembrie 1-3, București 050563, Romania

excerpt: Renaissance-style building designed by Petre Antonescu in the early 1900s for the Creţulescu family.
detail_description: The Kretzulescu Palace is a beautiful historical building that is known for its gothic and French renaissance architecture. It is one of the most ornate Bucharest attractions to visit, and it can take about an hour to see all of it.
name: "Crețulescu" Palace

excerpt: Weaponry through the ages, including swords & firearms, plus models of fortifications & transport.
detail_description: The National Military Museum, located between Bucharest Gara de Nord train station and the city center, boasts an extensive collection of original military artifacts. From authentic royal uniforms to gifts received by a former dictator from the British Royal family, the museum showcases a wide range of historical items. Visitors can marvel at everything from space mission landing capsules to XIXth century cannons, military decorations, and models of early aircraft designed by Romanian aviators.
name: The National Military Museum

excerpt: Synagogue inaugurated in the 1860s, designed to echo Vienna's neo-Moorish Leopoldstädter Tempel.
detail_description: The Choral Temple in Bucharest is a stunning synagogue modeled after Vienna's Leopoldstädter Tempel. Built in the 1860s, it was designed by Enderle and Freiwald and has undergone restoration after being devastated during World War II. The building is an iconic landmark, symbolizing Romanian culture and the arts. It hosts various cultural activities such as classical music concerts, exhibitions, and conferences.
name: The "Choral" Temple

excerpt: Former synagogue with exhibits on Romanian Jewish life & Jews' contributions to Romanian history.
detail_description: Jewish Museum Bucharest, located in the heart of the city, offers a captivating insight into the history, culture, and traditions of Romanian Jews. Housed in a former synagogue dating back to 1850, this museum showcases a valuable collection of artifacts, documents, and photographs that depict the Jewish community's contributions to Romanian society and its impact on the country's development.
name: Jewish Museum Bucharest

excerpt: Stylish specialty coffee shop by day, trendy cocktail bar by night, with a terrace & light snacks.
detail_description: Origo is a versatile establishment in Bucharest that transforms from a stylish specialty coffee shop during the day to a trendy cocktail bar at night. Located conveniently near the Old Centre, it offers some of the best brews in the city and provides an excellent starting point for exploring nearby attractions such as the Palace of the Parliament and Cismigiu Gardens. The café boasts a post-modern artsy decor, friendly English-speaking staff, and exclusively roasted top-class coffee.
name: Origo
